Objective

The objective of this notobook is to visually analyze Professor Chris Brooks ("Client") strava file after it is cleansed and structured for visual analysis. Once a visual analysis is performed, provide the client with some useful recommendations.

Background of client's file

The Client started increasing his exercise over the summer of 2019 and started collecting data on what he was doing. Throughout the summer he bought a variety of devices (heart rate monitor, watch, bicycle, etc.), and began publishing this data to the social sharing site 'strava'. The client requested an exploration of his 'strava' data dump to provide recommendations

Data Set used

This dataset was published to the social sharing site 'strava' from multiple devices. Details about each device were not provided. So it is important to analyze the dataset for consistency, missings, structure and values distribution in order to create a file for analysis purposes. The file obtained is comma separated and was saved locally in the root directory for reading purposes

$\qquad$Data Dictionary

$\qquad$Sources: Styr online Manual & Forerunner online Manual

    • Air Power: Power you produced that was needed to overcome wind resistance

    • Cadence: Cadence (stride rate) number of steps a runner takes per minute (SPM) or revolutions per minute (RPM).

    • Form Power: Power that is produced to maintain the runners individual form.Decreases in your Form Power over time, when running at similar training speeds, is a good indication that you have improved your running economy.

    • Ground Contact Time: Time your foot touches the ground each stride. Most running ground contact times are between 150 - 300 milliseconds. Elite runners are typically under 200-milliseconds

    • Leg Spring Stiffness: Leg Spring Stiffness is a measure of how well a runner recycles the energy applied to the ground.Correlated with running performance

    • Power: The shift in training time spent in each power zone is a direct indicator of the training progress and indirect indicator of the general improvement.Work rate and is a measurement of how much work you are doing and the rate of speed (how fast) you are doing it. Generated from vertical oscillation and cadence. Managing your running performance- Polar

    • Vertical Oscillation: Vertical oscillation measures the amount of bounce i.e. vertical up and down movement generated while running. Similar to ground contact time

    • Cadence: Cycling. The number of revolutions of the crank arm. Revolutions per minute (RPM).

    • Distance: Distance covered in meters

    • enhanced_altitude: Altitude in meters

    • enhanced_speed: Speed in m/s

    • fractional_cadence: Drop, only 2 cases

    • heart_rate: Heart rate is the speed of the heartbeat measured by the number of contractions of the heart per minute.

Dataset Cleansing and pre-Analysis

With the previous table, I decided to create an activity_type to separate the two type of activities, create date/time values I can use the the analysis, convert geo-positions to degrees. With the below code, we find that there are 49 unique Dates but 64 unique Datafiles. Indicating that there are days where Client engaged in excercise more than once. In order to keep cleaner analysis, it is recoomended to use Dates and Datafiles as keys in theanalysis Finally I will analyze dates and datafiles.

In [149]:
# Activity separation. Decision based on datapoints observed in previous cell and research to find field descriptions and 
# used Cadence as a base, but could have used another field with counts of 17847 (i.e. power)
df['activity_type'] = np.where(df.Cadence.isnull(),'Cycling','Running')   
# 'timestamp' is an object, converted from object to datetime. Then create a date field and a time field
df['timestamp'] = df['timestamp'].apply(lambda x: dt.datetime.strptime(x,'%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S'))
df['date'] = df['timestamp'].dt.date
df['time'] = df['timestamp'].dt.time                        # Alt: df['time'] = [dt.datetime.time(d) for d in df['timestamp']]
# Converting position longitude and latitude to degrees
df["position_long_degrees"] = df["position_long"] * ( 180 / 2**31 )
df["position_lat_degrees"] = df["position_lat"] * ( 180 / 2**31 )
df=df.drop(['position_long', 'position_lat'], axis=1)
# Check to see count and values of Unique dates and datafiles              
df=df.sort_values(by=['timestamp','datafile'])
print ('Number of Unique dates',len(df['date'].unique()))
print ('Number of Unique datafiles',len(df['datafile'].unique()))
df.groupby(['activity_type'])[['speed','Cadence']].count()

With the following plots grid, we can visually analyze the entire file and conclude the following:

  1. What fields can be used together: The cycling and running division seem to align well with the value ranges observed below
  2. Fields that seem ok to be used in both activities cadence enhanced_speed distance heart_rate enhanced_altitude
  3. What data anomalies are taking place: position_long_degrees seem to have an anomaly in a range
  4. What fields to exclude: fractional_cadence speed altitude

IMPORTANT: There are two ways in which data can be analyzed based on the activity type:

  1. Using data availability patterns. This assumes that the running activity is based on observations where data is observed in fields like Cadence, Form Power, etc.
  2. Based on enhanced_speed and distance.

This analysis is based on the assumption that approach 1 is the adecuate.

# Warnings are turned off because indexes are readjusted automatically and we want to visually avoid the warning
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
# Create a deepcopy for running only, so that we can filter out the cycling. Then drom fields we identified
# as not useful for running
rdf = copy.deepcopy(df)
rdf = rdf[df['activity_type']=='Running']
rdf = rdf[df['Cadence']!=0]
rdf.reset_index(inplace=True,drop=True)
rdf = rdf.drop(['fractional_cadence','speed','altitude','Cadence'], axis=1)
# Create a deepcopy for cycling only, so that we can filter out the running. Then drop fields we identified
# as not useful for cycling
cdf = copy.deepcopy(df)
cdf = cdf[df['activity_type']=='Cycling']
cdf=cdf[~pd.notnull(df['Cadence'])]
cdf.reset_index(inplace=True,drop=True)
cdf = cdf.drop(['fractional_cadence','speed','altitude','Air Power','Cadence','Form Power','Ground Time','Leg Spring Stiffness','Power','Vertical Oscillation'], axis=1)

In [154]:
# Creating a df to calculate the total time in each day (adding datafiles if occured the same day)
fmt = '%H:%M:%S'
maxdf=df.groupby(['date','datafile'])[['time']].max()
mindf=df.groupby(['date','datafile'])[['time']].min()
mindf= mindf.rename(columns={'time': 'time_min'})
cdfagg=pd.merge(left=maxdf,right=mindf,how='left', left_index=True, right_index=True)
cdfagg['time'] = pd.to_datetime(cdfagg['time'],format=fmt,errors='coerce')
cdfagg['time_min'] = pd.to_datetime(cdfagg['time_min'],format=fmt,errors='coerce')
cdfagg['session_time']=cdfagg['time']-cdfagg['time_min']
cdfagg['session_in_mins']=cdfagg['session_time'].apply(lambda x: x/np.timedelta64(1,'m'))
cdfagg.reset_index(inplace=True)
cleaned=cdfagg.groupby(['date'])[['session_in_mins']].sum()
# Histogram creation adding total session time to the chart
plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
chart=cleaned.plot(kind='bar',
                     color='dodgerblue')
chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(), rotation=90,fontsize=10)
chart.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mpl.ticker.StrMethodFormatter('{x:,.0f}'))
chart.tick_params(labelsize=8)
for p in chart.patches:
    height = p.get_height()
    chart.text(p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2.,
               height + 1,
               '{0:,.0f}'.format(height),
               ha="center",
               color='dimgray') 

plt.title('\n\nTotal workout time per day (both activities)\n',fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("Time in minutes", labelpad=16,fontsize=13)
plt.xlabel("Date", labelpad=16,fontsize=13)

#We first group the timestamp hbased on 10 min increments in a new df
cdf.set_index('timestamp',inplace=True)
c10avg=cdf.groupby(pd.Grouper(freq='600s')).mean()
c10avg = c10avg[c10avg['distance'].notna()]
c10avg.reset_index(inplace=True)
#We then use timestamp to create a new field that will look at 10 minuts increments as a scalar
c10avg['date'] = c10avg['timestamp'].dt.date
c10avg['time'] = c10avg['timestamp'].dt.time
incr=0
l=len(c10avg)
for i, row in c10avg.iterrows():
    c10avg.loc[i,'time_interval']=incr
    if i != l-1:
        if c10avg.loc[i,'date'] == c10avg.loc[i+1,'date']:
            incr=incr+5
        else:
            incr=0
    else:
        incr=incr+5
ts=c10avg.groupby(['time_interval'])[['cadence','heart_rate','enhanced_speed']].mean()
ts.reset_index(inplace=True)
# With the new time series df, we plot heart rate and enhanced speed to see the trend
plt.figure(figsize=(12,3))
plt.plot(ts["time_interval"], ts["enhanced_speed"],'r-', label="enhanced_speed")
plt.gca().set_xlabel("At \"X\" Minutes")
plt.gca().twinx()
plt.plot(ts["time_interval"], ts["heart_rate"],'b-', label="heart_rate")
plt.title("\nAverage Cadence and Heart Rate in 10 minutes increments (cycling) \n", fontsize=14)
plt.gcf().legend(loc=3)
plt.gcf().axes[0].set_ylabel("Speed (m/s)")
plt.gcf().axes[1].set_ylabel("Heart Rate")
